# Privilege Escalation

## Objective
Simulate an attacker escalating a compromised low-privilege account to full administrator rights by creating a new account and adding it to the local Administrators group.

## Commands Run

| Step | Command | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `whoami` / `net user %USERNAME%` | Check current account and group memberships |
| 2 | `net user SOCLabUser P@ssw0rd123! /add` | Creates a harmless local test account |
| 3 | `net localgroup Administrators SOCLabUser /add` | **Simulated privilege escalation** — adds the account to Administrators |
| 4 | `net localgroup Administrators` | Verifies `SOCLabUser` now appears as an administrator |

**Clean-up:**
```
net localgroup Administrators SOCLabUser /delete
net user SOCLabUser /delete
```

## What to Look For in Wazuh
- User added to a local group
- Administrator group modified
- Windows Security Event IDs: **4720** (user created), **4732** (member added to a local group)

## Investigation — Wazuh Alert

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| agent.name | Windows11 |
| rule.description | Administrators Group Changed |
| rule.id | 60154 |
| rule.level | 12 |
| timestamp | Jul 9, 2026 @ 14:55:35.524 |
| data.win.system.eventID | 4732 |

## Takeaway
This produced the highest-severity alert in the lab (level 12) — modifying the Administrators group is treated as one of the most critical events Wazuh watches for, since it directly grants elevated access.
